<%-include("header.ejs") %>

<body class="bg-gray-100">

    <!-- Header Section -->
    <header class="bg-orange-600 text-white py-6">
        <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
            <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-center">Indian Traditions</h1>
            <p class="text-center text-lg mt-2">Discover the Rich Cultural Heritage of India</p>
        </div>
    </header>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <main class="max-w-7xl mx-auto py-10 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

        <!-- Section 1: Diwali -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Diwali - The Festival of Lights</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Diwali, also known as Deepavali, is one of the most popular festivals in India. It symbolizes the
                        victory of light over darkness and good over evil. People celebrate by lighting oil lamps,
                        bursting fireworks, and sharing sweets.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Diwali Celebration" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 2: Holi -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Holi Celebration" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Holi - The Festival of Colors</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Holi is a vibrant festival celebrated across India. It marks the arrival of spring and the victory
                        of good over evil. People play with colors, dance to traditional songs, and enjoy festive foods
                        like gujiya and thandai.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 3: Navratri -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Navratri - The Nine Nights Festival</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Navratri is a nine-night festival dedicated to the worship of Goddess Durga. It is celebrated
                        with great devotion, especially in Gujarat and West Bengal. The festival includes fasting,
                        traditional dances like Garba and Dandiya, and cultural performances.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Navratri Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 4: Pongal -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Pongal Celebration" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Pongal - The Harvest Festival</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Pongal is a harvest festival celebrated in Tamil Nadu. It is a four-day festival that honors the
                        Sun God and the prosperity brought by a good harvest. Traditional dishes like Pongal are prepared
                        and shared among families and communities.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 5: Onam -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Onam - The Harvest Festival of Kerala</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Onam is a major harvest festival celebrated in Kerala. It is marked by elaborate feasts,
                        traditional dances, boat races, and flower decorations. The festival commemorates the homecoming
                        of the legendary King Mahabali.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Onam Celebration" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 6: Makar Sankranti -->
         
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Makar Sankranti Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Makar Sankranti - The Kite Festival</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Makar Sankranti is celebrated in various parts of India, marking the transition of the Sun into
                        Capricorn. The festival is known for its kite-flying competitions, especially in Gujarat, and
                        traditional sweets made of sesame and jaggery.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 7: Baisakhi -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Baisakhi - The Harvest Festival of Punjab</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Baisakhi is a significant festival in Punjab, celebrating the harvest of Rabi crops. It also marks
                        the formation of the Khalsa by Guru Gobind Singh. The festival is celebrated with traditional
                        music, dance (Bhangra), and feasts.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Baisakhi Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 8: Raksha Bandhan -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Raksha Bandhan Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Raksha Bandhan - The Bond of Protection</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Raksha Bandhan is a festival celebrating the bond between brothers and sisters. Sisters tie a
                        protective thread (Rakhi) on their brothers' wrists, and brothers vow to protect them. The
                        festival is marked by the exchange of gifts and sweets.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 9: Ganesh Chaturthi -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Ganesh Chaturthi - The Festival of Lord
                        Ganesha</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Ganesh Chaturthi is a major Hindu festival celebrated with great fervor, especially in
                        Maharashtra. It marks the birth of Lord Ganesha, the remover of obstacles. The festival includes
                        the installation of Ganesha idols, prayers, and processions.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Ganesh Chaturthi Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 10: Janmashtami -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Janmashtami Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Janmashtami - The Birth of Lord Krishna</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Janmashtami celebrates the birth of Lord Krishna, the eighth incarnation of Vishnu. The festival
                        is observed with fasting, singing devotional songs, and reenacting episodes from Krishna's life.
                        The Dahi Handi competition is a major highlight in Maharashtra.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 11: Eid-ul-Fitr -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Eid-ul-Fitr - The Festival of Breaking the
                        Fast</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Eid-ul-Fitr marks the end of Ramadan, the Islamic holy month of fasting. The festival is
                        celebrated with communal prayers, feasting, and giving charity to the poor. It is a time of joy
                        and gratitude for the blessings received during Ramadan.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Eid-ul-Fitr Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 12: Durga Puja -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Durga Puja Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Durga Puja - The Victory of Goddess Durga</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Durga Puja is a major festival in West Bengal and other parts of India. It celebrates the victory
                        of Goddess Durga over the buffalo demon Mahishasura. The festival is marked by elaborate
                        decorations, idol worship, cultural performances, and feasting.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 13: Karva Chauth -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Karva Chauth - The Fast for Marital Bliss</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Karva Chauth is a traditional festival where married women fast from sunrise to moonrise for the
                        well-being and longevity of their husbands. The festival is popular in North India and is
                        celebrated with great devotion and rituals.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Karva Chauth Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 14: Christmas -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Christmas Celebration"
                    class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Christmas - The Birth of Jesus Christ</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Christmas is celebrated by Christians across India to commemorate the birth of Jesus Christ. The
                        festival is marked by midnight masses, decorating Christmas trees, exchanging gifts, and
                        preparing traditional foods like plum cake.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 15: Lohri -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-center">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-orange-700 mb-4">Lohri - The Bonfire Festival</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-700 text-lg mb-4">
                        Lohri is a popular festival in Punjab, celebrated in the middle of January. It marks the end of
                        winter and the harvesting of the Rabi crops. The festival is celebrated with bonfires, singing
                        traditional songs, and dancing to the beats of the dhol.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/600x400" alt="Lohri Celebration" class="rounded-lg shadow-lg">
            </div>
        </section>

    </main>

    <!-- Footer Section -->
    <footer class="bg-orange-600 text-white py-4">
        <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center">
            <p class="text-lg">Â© 2024 Indian Traditions. All rights reserved.</p>
        </div>
    </footer>

</body>

</html>
